[1] The speaker is a true champion of the female voice, an adviser of poverty, gender and development for the World Bank, United Nations and several NGOs in India and the world over. Some parents sometimes constrain,confine and crush the girls to raise good girls. In India, they call this “adjusting”. To understand the roots of abuse, she started asking the simple question “What does it mean to you to be a good woman or a good man today?”. We think the world has changed, but external changes are extremely misleading. Because on the inside, we have not changed. For her research, She identified seven habits that delete women, that make women disappear. To change these systems, women need men.                                                                                                                                                                                          
[2] In India, recall “ adjusting”. No matter what happens “just adjust”. She started to research the root of the views of the state of women and men in Delhi. Don’t speak, Be quiet…. Be a people please, please otters, Everyone likes nice women who always smile, never angry, never say No.You have no sexuality. Women don’t take education about her bodies. Don’t believe women. Duty or desire. Be totally dependent. Women have to depend on other aspects of all things. The habit is the foundation of all society in India. Habit 4 is “you have no sexuality.”. Habit 5 is “ Don’t trust women.”. Habit 6 is “Duty over desire.”. Habit 7 is “Be totally dependent.”. Women have to depend on men to survive. These habits are personality problems for men and women.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                
[4] In her talk, she explained about 7 habits that make women disappear in Indian middle and upper class families. These habits are “no body, no voice, be others people, no sexuality, do not trust women, duty of desire, and depend on man”. These habits are seen as a good thing in society, but in fact, they take away women’s rights and keep men in high class. She said that it really changes a new definition of what it means to be a “good woman” and “good man”. Mens must join these changes, listen without blame. Also, stand with women. If half a billion women and men work together, society can be changed. After her speech, the master of this event realized that he sometimes asked his daughter the same things. He promised to change and tell her to do whatever you want. Speeches ended by saying that if we stop repeating these habits, women, men, and the world can truly change.

[5] I think that the speaker’s research is profoundly relevant not just to India, but also to Japan and other societies where women are culturally pressured to prioritize the needs of others. The habits she identifies, like being quiet, pleasing people, and prioritizing duty over desire, are deeply embedded in the Japanese concept of a good woman. This shows that achieving gender equality requires more than just laws; it demands a fundamental shift in our invisible cultural compass. The most crucial takeaway is the need to redefine what it means to be a good woman and a good man, as this is the bedrock of societal change. Men must step up to change these learned behaviors, not just women.
